:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>&lt;p>In most contexts individuals and groups differ in their relative power. Some people are in a better position to influence and control others. Differences in power can be observed in dyadic relationships, groups, organisations, within society, and between nations. Recent advances in psychological research highlight that power has far reaching consequences for the individual. Power alters basic cognitive processes and changes the way individuals form judgments and engage in courses of action. For example, powerful individuals are more inclined to act and judge in line with their current feelings as compared to powerless individuals (Weick &amp;amp; Guinote, 2008a). A greater focus on desired states also makes people in power more prone to error in their forecasts (Weick &amp;amp; Guinote, 2008b). The aim of this ESRC project is to conduct research into the physiological underpinnings of these effects of power. The project examines how powerful and powerless differ in their physiological responses (eg hemispheric brain activation; cardiovascular activity), and how differences at the physiological level contribute to overt differences in the judgments and actions of powerful and powerless individuals.&lt;/p></gtr:abstractText><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2010-04-07</gtr:end><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE"><gtr:id>924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE</gtr:id><gtr:name>ESRC</gtr:name></gtr:funder><gtr:start>2009-02-01</gtr:start><gtr:type>INCOME_ACTUAL</gtr:type><gtr:valuePounds>87487</gtr:valuePounds></gtr:fund><gtr:output><gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutputs/><gtr:collaborationOutputs/><gtr:disseminationOutputs/><gtr:exploitationOutputs/><gtr:furtherFundingOutputs><gtr:furtherFundingOutput><gtr:amountPounds>21326</gtr:amountPounds><gtr:country>United Kingdom of Great Britain &amp; Northern Ireland (UK)</gtr:country><gtr:currCode>GBP</gtr:currCode><gtr:currCountryCode>United Kingdo